e:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>a valid reason that they can justify</li>\n  <li>acted reasonably in the circumstances</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>They must also:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>be consistent - eg not dismiss you for doing something that they let other employees do</li>\n  <li>have investigated the situation fully before dismissing you - eg if a complaint was made about you</li>\n</ul>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>If you’re a part-time or fixed-term worker, you can’t be treated less favourably than a full-time or permanent employee.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>Notice period</h2>\n<p>You must be given at least the notice stated in your contract or the statutory minimum notice period, whichever is longer. </p>\n\n<p>There are some situations where you can be <a href=\"/dismissal/reasons-you-can-be-dismissed\" title=\"When you can be dismissed\">dismissed immediately</a> - eg for violence.</p>\n\n<h2>Getting your dismissal in writing</h2>\n\n<p>You have the right to ask for a written statement from your employer giving the reasons why you&rsquo;ve been dismissed if you&rsquo;re:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>an employee and have completed one year’s service</li>\n  <li>employed under a fixed-term contract which has ended and not been renewed</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Your employer must supply the statement within 14 days of you asking for it.</p>\n\n<p>If you&rsquo;re dismissed while you are on Statutory <a href=\"/maternity-leave\" title=\"Maternity Leave\">Maternity Leave</a>, your employer must give you a written statement. You get this:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>even if you&rsquo;ve not asked for one</li>\n  <li>regardless of how long you&rsquo;ve worked for your employer</li>\n</ul>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>If you’re unsure of your employment status, speak to your employer or <a href=\"/employment-status\" title=\"Check your employment status\">check your employment status</a>.</p>\n</div>\n\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/dismissal/reasons-you-can-be-dismissed","slug":"reasons-you-can-be-dismissed","order":2,"title":"Reasons you can be dismissed","body":"<p>There are some situations when your employer can dismiss you fairly.</p>\n\n<h2>Not being able to do your job properly</h2>\n<p>You may not be able to do your job properly if, for example, you:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>haven&rsquo;t been able to keep up with important changes to your job - eg a new computer system</li>\n  <li>can&rsquo;t get along with your colleagues</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Before taking any action, your employer should:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>follow disciplinary procedures - eg warn you that your work isn&rsquo;t satisfactory</li>\n  <li>give you a chance to improve - eg by training you</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Illness</h2>\n<p>You can be dismissed if you have a persistent or long-term illness that makes it impossible for you to do your job.</p>\n\n<p>Before taking any action, your employer should:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>look for ways to support you - eg considering whether the job itself is making you sick and needs changing</li>\n  <li>give you reasonable time to recover from your illness</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>If you have a disability (which may include long-term illness), your employer has a legal duty to <a href=\"/rights-disabled-person/employment\" title=\"Employment rights if you're disabled\">support disability in the workplace</a>.</p>\n\n<p>Dismissal because of a disability may be unlawful discrimination.</p>\n\n<h2>Redundancy</h2>\n<p>Redundancy is a form of dismissal and is fair in most cases.</p>\n\n<p>If the reason you are selected for <a href=\"/redundant-your-rights\" title=\"Redundancy\">redundancy</a> is unfair then you will have been unfairly dismissed.</p>\n\n<h2>Summary dismissal</h2>\n<p>You can be dismissed for &lsquo;gross misconduct&rsquo; without your employer going through the normal disciplinary procedures.  This can happen if, for example, you&rsquo;re violent towards a colleague, customer or property.</p>\n\n<p>Your employer should always investigate the circumstances before making a dismissal, even in possible gross misconduct cases.</p>\n\n<h2>A &lsquo;statutory restriction&rsquo;</h2>\n<p>You can be dismissed if continuing to employ you would break the law - eg if you&rsquo;re a driver in a lorry firm and you lose your driving licence.</p>\n\n<h2>It&rsquo;s impossible to carry on employing you</h2>\n<p>If it&rsquo;s impossible to carry on employing you, it&rsquo;s likely to be fair. For example, if a factory burns down and it&rsquo;s no longer possible to employ anyone.</p>\n\n<h2>A &lsquo;substantial reason&rsquo;</h2>\n<p>You may be dismissed fairly if, for example:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>you unreasonably refuse to accept a company reorganisation that changes your employment terms</li>\n  <li>you&rsquo;re sent to prison</li>\n</ul>\n\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/dismissal/unfair-and-constructive-dismissal","slug":"unfair-and-constructive-dismissal","order":3,"title":"Unfair and constructive dismissal","body":"<p>In certain situations, you may be able to take legal action if you&rsquo;re dismissed.</p>\n\n<h2>Unfair dismissal</h2>\n<p>Your dismissal could be unfair if your employer doesn&rsquo;t:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>have a good reason for dismissing you</li>\n  <li>follow the company&rsquo;s formal disciplinary or dismissal process (or the statutory minimum dismissal procedure in Northern Ireland)</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Situations when your dismissal is likely to be unfair include if you:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>asked for flexible working</li>\n  <li>refused to give up your working time rights - eg to take rest breaks</li>\n  <li>resigned and gave the correct <a href=\"/handing-in-your-notice-resigning-leaving-job\" title=\"Handing in your notice\">notice period</a>    </li>\n  <li>joined a <a href=\"/join-trade-union\" title=\"Trade unions\">trade union</a></li>\n  <li>took part in legal industrial action that lasted 12 weeks or less</li>\n  <li>needed time off for jury service</li>\n  <li>applied for maternity, paternity and adoption leave</li>\n  <li>were on any maternity, paternity and adoption leave you&rsquo;re entitled to</li>\n  <li>tried to enforce your right to receive Working Tax Credits</li>\n  <li>exposed wrongdoing in the workplace (<a href=\"/whistleblowing/dismissals-and-whistleblowing\" title=\"dismissals and whistleblowing\">whistleblowing</a>)</li>\n  <li>were forced to retire (known as &lsquo;compulsory retirement&rsquo;)</li>\n</ul>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>Compulsory retirement is not allowed unless your employer can objectively justify it, but you can challenge it at an <a href=\"/employment-tribunals\" title=\"take your employer to an employment tribunal\">employment tribunal</a>.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>Constructive dismissal</h2>\n<p>Constructive dismissal is when you&rsquo;re forced to leave your job against your will because of your <strong>employer&rsquo;s</strong> conduct.</p>\n\n<p>The reasons you leave your job must be serious, for example, they:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>don&rsquo;t pay you or suddenly demote you for no reason</li>\n  <li>force you to accept unreasonable changes to how you work - eg tell you to work night shifts when your contract is only for day work</li>\n  <li>let other employees harass or bully you</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Your employer&rsquo;s breach of contract may be one serious incident or a series of incidents that are serious when taken together.</p>\n\n<p>You should try and sort any issues out by speaking to your employer to solve the dispute.</p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>If you do have a case for constructive dismissal, you should leave your job immediately - your employer may argue that, by staying, you accepted the conduct or treatment.</p>\n</div>\n\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/dismissal/what-to-do-if-youre-dismissed","slug":"what-to-do-if-youre-dismissed","order":4,"title":"What to do if you're dismissed","body":"<p>If you&rsquo;re threatened with dismissal (or are dismissed) you can get help from a third party to solve the issue by mediation, conciliation and arbitration.</p>\n\n<p>If you&rsquo;re a member of a trade union, you can also speak to your union representative.</p>\n\n<h2>Employment tribunals</h2>\n<p>If you&rsquo;ve been unable to solve a problem between you and your employer, you can normally go to an <a href=\"/employment-tribunals\" title=\"Employment tribunals\">employment tribunal.</a> In Northern Ireland, you would go to an industrial tribunal.</p>\n\n<h3>Qualifying period to claim unfair dismissal</h3>\n<p>You must have worked for your employer for a minimum period before you qualify for the right to claim unfair dismissal at a tribunal. If you&rsquo;re classed as an <a href=\"/employment-status\" title=\"Employment status\">employee</a> and started your job: </p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>on or after 6 April 2012 - the qualifying period is normally 2 years  </li>\n  <li>before 6 April 2012 - the qualifying period is normally one year</li>\n</ul>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>In Northern Ireland, the qualifying period is still normally one year.</p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice help-notice\">\n<p>In unfair dismissal claims you must make the claim to a tribunal within 3 months of being dismissed.</p>\n</div>\n\n"}]},"updated_at":"2012-11-06T14:17:34+00:00","tags":[{"title":"Redundancies, dismissals and disciplinaries","id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/tags/working%2Fredundancies-dismissals.json","web_url":null,"details":{"description":"Includes solving a workplace dispute, calculating redundancy pay and dismissal","short_description":null,"type":"section"},"content_with_tag":{"id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/with_tag.json?tag=working%2Fredundancies-dismissals","web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/browse/working/redundancies-dismissals"},"parent":{"title":"Working, jobs and pensions","id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/tags/working.json","web_url":null,"details":{"description":"Includes holidays and fin